1
00:00:33,491 --> 00:00:34,576
[crowd cheering]

2
00:00:35,076 --> 00:00:36,077
[Jordan] <i>Thank you.</i>

3
00:00:36,870 --> 00:00:39,080
To all the fans in the city of Chicago,

4
00:00:40,415 --> 00:00:43,585
if you guys remember in 1984
when they drafted Michael Jordan...

5
00:00:47,047 --> 00:00:48,715
<i>I said then, when I got here,</i>

6
00:00:48,798 --> 00:00:50,638
<i>that we would be champions
by the time I leave.</i>

7
00:00:50,717 --> 00:00:53,470
- [man] Here they are.
- [Jordan] This is what you're looking for.

8
00:00:56,181 --> 00:00:58,349
<i>Well, we are five-time champions,
going for six,</i>

9
00:00:59,434 --> 00:01:02,103
<i>and we need your support.
Thank you very, very much.</i>

10
00:01:02,187 --> 00:01:03,313
[crowd cheering]

11
00:01:28,713 --> 00:01:31,953
[reporter] <i>You have any sense of destiny,
you know, why is all this meant for you,</i>

12
00:01:32,008 --> 00:01:35,095
<i>and what's down the road,
or are you just taking it a day at a time?</i>

13
00:01:35,595 --> 00:01:39,307
I just want the franchise and
Chicago Bulls to be respected as a team...

14
00:01:40,308 --> 00:01:44,187
like the Lakers or Philadelphia 76ers
or the Boston Celtics.

15
00:01:44,270 --> 00:01:49,067
It's very hard for something like that
to happen, but it's not impossible.

16
00:01:49,150 --> 00:01:51,778
But hopefully, I, and this team

17
00:01:51,861 --> 00:01:54,739
and this whole organization
can build a program like that.

18
00:01:59,786 --> 00:02:02,997
[commentator] <i>Michael Jordan...
with 30 points.</i>

19
00:02:03,581 --> 00:02:09,587
<i>And the Chicago Bulls have won
their first-ever NBA championship.</i>

20
00:02:14,300 --> 00:02:16,302
["Been Around the World" playing]

21
00:02:19,222 --> 00:02:21,391
[commentator] <i>There's Jordan for three!</i>

22
00:02:24,269 --> 00:02:26,062
<i>They have done it again!</i>

23
00:02:27,230 --> 00:02:28,690
<i>Now, Pippen gets a snatch.</i>

24
00:02:29,440 --> 00:02:32,277
<i>There's Paxson for three! Yes!</i>

25
00:02:32,360 --> 00:02:36,072
<i>For three straight NBA championships.</i>

26
00:02:36,614 --> 00:02:39,951
[reporter] <i>Debate will now rage about
whether they are the best team ever.</i>

27
00:02:40,535 --> 00:02:44,372
<i>They're not just great athletes. They're
a fascinating assortment of personalities.</i>

28
00:02:44,455 --> 00:02:47,750
The most famous man on the planet is here!

29
00:02:47,834 --> 00:02:48,834
[crowd cheering]

30
00:02:49,544 --> 00:02:54,340
My name is Michael Jordan.
I played with the Bulls from '84 to '98.

31
00:02:54,424 --> 00:02:58,052
Took an 18-month vacation, hiatus.

32
00:02:58,678 --> 00:03:02,015
So I would say that 13 years
that I played with the Bulls.

33
00:03:02,640 --> 00:03:08,146
Please welcome from the Chicago Bulls,
all-star forward Scottie Pippen!

34
00:03:08,229 --> 00:03:09,355
[crowd cheering]

35
00:03:10,857 --> 00:03:14,777
Scottie Maurice Pippen
from Hamburg, Arkansas.

36
00:03:15,904 --> 00:03:17,864
[commentator] <i>Great passing! Oh!</i>

37
00:03:17,947 --> 00:03:22,160
<i>Baby! It looked like
he shifted gears mid-air.</i>

38
00:03:23,703 --> 00:03:27,373
He has led the NBA in rebounds
for the last five years.

39
00:03:27,457 --> 00:03:29,667
Please welcome back Dennis Rodman.

40
00:03:29,751 --> 00:03:31,920
Dennis Rodman. What's up?

41
00:03:33,046 --> 00:03:36,382
I was shocked the Chicago Bulls
even asked me to come.

42
00:03:36,466 --> 00:03:38,384
I think
I was a little more eccentric for them.

43
00:03:38,468 --> 00:03:40,637
[man] <i>There's something about you
that's frightening.</i>

44
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:41,840
Is it because I'm different?

45
00:03:42,388 --> 00:03:46,017
[commentator 1] <i>And Rodman just kicked the
photographer! The photographer is hurt.</i>

46
00:03:46,100 --> 00:03:48,811
[commentator 2] <i>That is the last
we will see of Dennis Rodman.</i>

47
00:03:50,605 --> 00:03:54,359
At the heart of this team
is a rare spirit, coach Phil Jackson.

48
00:03:54,901 --> 00:03:57,946
We created an image
that people wanted to be part of.

49
00:03:58,029 --> 00:03:59,530
I think that's all you can hope for.

50
00:04:00,490 --> 00:04:03,284
[commentator] <i>The Chicago Bulls have won</i>

51
00:04:04,202 --> 00:04:07,330
<i>the '96 NBA championship!</i>

52
00:04:07,413 --> 00:04:09,874
[reporter] <i>What's unique
about this particular dynasty?</i>

53
00:04:10,124 --> 00:04:12,418
I guess what's unique is that,
we're, uh...

54
00:04:13,544 --> 00:04:15,213
You know, we've got Michael. [laughs]

55
00:04:15,296 --> 00:04:22,220
[fans chanting] Michael! Michael!
Michael! Michael!

56
00:04:23,054 --> 00:04:24,097
[screaming]

57
00:04:24,180 --> 00:04:25,500
[reporter] Why is everybody here?

58
00:04:25,556 --> 00:04:27,058
- Michael Jordan.
- Michael Jordan.

59
00:04:27,141 --> 00:04:29,352
Everybody loves Chicago Bulls
and Michael Jordan.

60
00:04:30,395 --> 00:04:31,771
[car honking]

61
00:04:37,318 --> 00:04:39,237
[commentator] <i>...was about to do.</i>

62
00:04:39,320 --> 00:04:43,074
<i>Five seconds remaining in regulation.
The inbound...</i>

63
00:04:44,325 --> 00:04:46,577
<i>Pippen rolls it to Kukoc!</i>

64
00:04:46,661 --> 00:04:51,791
<i>Chicago Bulls have won
their fifth championship</i>

65
00:04:51,874 --> 00:04:53,668
<i>in the last seven years!</i>

66
00:04:54,669 --> 00:04:57,588
<i>It is bedlam here at the United Center.</i>

67
00:04:57,672 --> 00:04:59,340
[crowd cheering]

68
00:05:01,634 --> 00:05:03,261
[reporter 1] <i>To hometown Chicago fans,</i>

69
00:05:03,344 --> 00:05:06,639
<i>winning the big one is starting to feel
almost like a constitutional right</i>

70
00:05:06,723 --> 00:05:10,310
<i>as the Bulls took
their fifth NBA title on Friday night.</i>

71
00:05:11,352 --> 00:05:16,441
[reporter 2] <i>Count them. One, two, three,
four and five NBA championship trophies.</i>

72
00:05:16,524 --> 00:05:19,110
[reporter 3] <i>As hundreds of thousands
of fans cheered the Bulls,</i>

73
00:05:19,193 --> 00:05:20,653
<i>the drama of what will happen</i>

74
00:05:20,737 --> 00:05:23,406
<i>to this great dynasty
was apparent to all...</i>

75
00:05:23,489 --> 00:05:26,451
[Reinsdorf] After the fifth championship,
which was '96-'97,

76
00:05:27,994 --> 00:05:32,123
we were looking at this team
and we realized, other than Michael,

77
00:05:32,206 --> 00:05:36,878
the rest of the guys were probably
at the end of their high-productive years.

78
00:05:37,920 --> 00:05:41,257
We had to decide
whether we keep the team together or not,

79
00:05:41,341 --> 00:05:44,677
and we realized
maybe this was the time to do a rebuild

80
00:05:44,761 --> 00:05:46,387
and not try to win a sixth championship.

81
00:05:46,471 --> 00:05:47,990
[reporter 1]<i>Â Can they
keep the team together?</i>

82
00:05:48,014 --> 00:05:49,450
[reporter 2]
<i>Is there any doubt Michael...</i>

83
00:05:49,474 --> 00:05:51,851
[reporter 3] <i>Questions about
the future of Phil Jackson.</i>

84
00:05:51,934 --> 00:05:53,811
<i>Will this be his last year?</i>

85
00:05:53,895 --> 00:05:56,332
[reporter 4] <i>How will the Bulls
deal with their aging stars...</i>

86
00:05:56,356 --> 00:05:59,650
[reporter 5] <i>...becoming something
transcendent, you can see it evaporating.</i>

87
00:06:02,737 --> 00:06:07,200
I just kept hearing this over and over,
and I was just getting irritated, like...

88
00:06:07,658 --> 00:06:08,785
We were winning.

89
00:06:08,868 --> 00:06:09,868
[cheering]

90
00:06:10,828 --> 00:06:14,457
We felt like
we were the greatest team ever.

91
00:06:14,540 --> 00:06:16,501
[reporter] <i>You have to wonder
why Michael Jordan,</i>

92
00:06:16,584 --> 00:06:20,713
<i>who is surely the most popular player
in our time, would be, in effect,</i>

93
00:06:20,797 --> 00:06:22,590
<i>driven out of professional basketball.</i>

94
00:06:31,974 --> 00:06:33,476
[commentator 1] <i>A spectacular move!</i>

95
00:06:33,559 --> 00:06:35,186
[commentator 2]<i> The game's over!</i>

96
00:06:35,269 --> 00:06:37,563
[commentator 3]
<i>Chicago Stadium is going wild!</i>

97
00:06:39,524 --> 00:06:42,026
[Jackson] <i>First of all, there's
no backstabbing going on here.</i>

98
00:06:42,110 --> 00:06:43,068
<i>It's time for me to move on.</i>

99
00:06:43,069 --> 00:06:45,469
[Krause] <i>This will be Phil's last year
as coach of the Bulls.</i>

100
00:06:48,074 --> 00:06:50,636
- [man 1] <i>Are the expectations too high?</i>
- [man 2] <i>Where do we go from here?</i>

101
00:06:50,660 --> 00:06:53,162
[woman] <i>The only question:
how long can it last?</i>

102
00:07:02,463 --> 00:07:03,673
[crowd cheering]

103
00:07:06,592 --> 00:07:11,013
[Wilbon] So, going into 1997-98,
the Bulls have won five championships.

104
00:07:11,848 --> 00:07:13,266
There's drama that summer

105
00:07:13,349 --> 00:07:16,602
as to whether they're gonna come back,
although I think most of us

106
00:07:16,686 --> 00:07:20,606
who are from Chicago and call Chicago home
knew somehow they'd be back.

107
00:07:22,942 --> 00:07:24,944
Jerry Reinsdorf, the majority owner...

108
00:07:26,028 --> 00:07:28,239
would have to leave town
if they didn't come back.

109
00:07:28,322 --> 00:07:31,951
You can't argue with championship
after championship after championship.

110
00:07:32,702 --> 00:07:35,037
They were still the best team in the NBA.

111
00:07:35,913 --> 00:07:39,500
You have Scottie Pippen,
an incredibly talented athlete,

112
00:07:39,584 --> 00:07:40,960
very skilled scorer.

113
00:07:41,043 --> 00:07:44,172
His mental sharpness
and his court awareness

114
00:07:44,255 --> 00:07:47,592
and his basketball savvy made him
the greatest number-two player ever.

115
00:07:49,093 --> 00:07:52,972
Dennis Rodman was the defensive presence,
the rebounder,

116
00:07:53,055 --> 00:07:56,309
someone who, on a team with big egos,
didn't need the ball.

117
00:07:57,018 --> 00:07:59,270
And he never ran out of energy,
that was the thing.

118
00:07:59,353 --> 00:08:00,897
Whoo!

119
00:08:00,980 --> 00:08:05,818
[Wilbon] At that point, Michael Jordan's
already the ultimate sports alpha male.

120
00:08:06,527 --> 00:08:10,114
I mean, the only comparisons
that I can recall being apt

121
00:08:10,198 --> 00:08:13,326
were to Babe Ruth and Muhammad Ali.

122
00:08:13,910 --> 00:08:16,662
That's it. That's the list.
There's nobody else on it.

123
00:08:17,246 --> 00:08:18,664
[reporter] Michael, obviously,

124
00:08:18,748 --> 00:08:21,626
in the wake of this
incredible celebration,

125
00:08:21,709 --> 00:08:24,504
there'll be some
very difficult business decisions.

126
00:08:25,129 --> 00:08:29,133
We are entitled to defend what we have
until we lose it.

127
00:08:29,842 --> 00:08:32,762
If we lose it, then you look at it
and say, "Okay, let's change.

128
00:08:32,845 --> 00:08:35,556
Let's just go through a rebuilding."

129
00:08:35,640 --> 00:08:40,311
No one's guaranteeing rebuilding's
gonna be two or three, four, five years.

130
00:08:40,978 --> 00:08:43,231
Cubs have been rebuilding for 42 years.

131
00:08:43,314 --> 00:08:44,314
[people laughing]

132
00:08:47,860 --> 00:08:50,029
If you wanna look at this
from a business thing,

133
00:08:50,988 --> 00:08:54,408
have a sense of respect for the people
who have laid the groundworks

134
00:08:54,492 --> 00:08:57,036
so that you could be
a profitable organization.

135
00:09:39,370 --> 00:09:42,331
[Jordan] <i>We had just finished
winning a fifth title.</i>

136
00:09:45,793 --> 00:09:49,839
<i>It's a lot of uncertainty,
and management started talking about</i>

137
00:09:49,922 --> 00:09:53,134
<i>the franchise is gonna change
or we're gonna rebuild.</i>

138
00:09:53,718 --> 00:09:55,303
<i>I thought it was unfair.</i>

139
00:09:56,470 --> 00:10:00,891
<i>I would never let someone
who's not putting on a uniform</i>

140
00:10:01,642 --> 00:10:05,896
<i>and playing each and every dayÂ dictate
what we do on the basketball court.</i>

141
00:10:09,108 --> 00:10:12,778
<i>So, you know, my mentality was,
"Let's put things aside,</i>

142
00:10:12,862 --> 00:10:15,781
<i>you know, from a business sense
and focus on that craft.</i>

143
00:10:15,865 --> 00:10:18,534
<i>Let's give them a reason
not to think that way."</i>

144
00:10:21,704 --> 00:10:25,166
[reporter] <i>Michael Jordan waded into
the undertone of bitterness on the Bulls</i>

145
00:10:25,249 --> 00:10:28,294
<i>when asked what the Bulls'
biggest challenge would be this year.</i>

146
00:10:29,629 --> 00:10:31,797
- Um... [laughs]
- [reporters laugh]

147
00:10:32,423 --> 00:10:35,468
[reporter] <i>Michael glancing up
at the office of GM Jerry Krause.</i>

148
00:10:39,347 --> 00:10:42,391
[Telander] Jerry Krause was the
general manager of the Bulls,

149
00:10:43,100 --> 00:10:45,853
and he was certainly at the root of

150
00:10:45,936 --> 00:10:49,231
what made the tension
of that season so severe.

151
00:10:53,319 --> 00:10:55,738
[Reinsdorf] Jerry Krause was a scout
for the White Sox.

152
00:10:55,821 --> 00:10:58,491
He was there
when I bought the White Sox in 1981.

153
00:10:59,033 --> 00:11:01,827
And after I bought the Bulls,
he came to see me.

154
00:11:01,911 --> 00:11:04,372
<i>Said he'd like to be
general manager of the Bulls.</i>

155
00:11:04,455 --> 00:11:06,791
If everybody's ready, we can get started.

156
00:11:06,874 --> 00:11:08,394
[Reinsdorf] <i>I asked around the league,</i>

157
00:11:08,459 --> 00:11:11,003
<i>and everybody I talked to said,
"Don't touch the guy."</i>

158
00:11:11,420 --> 00:11:13,422
Yeah, he had a way of alienating people.

159
00:11:14,590 --> 00:11:17,760
But I wasn't hiring somebody
to win a personality contest.

160
00:11:17,843 --> 00:11:21,097
I wanted somebody who
truly believed in building a team

161
00:11:21,180 --> 00:11:23,432
the way I wanted to,
and Krause was the guy.

162
00:11:24,809 --> 00:11:27,895
[Vancil] To his credit, he did his job.

163
00:11:28,979 --> 00:11:29,979
But...

164
00:11:30,314 --> 00:11:32,066
Jerry had the "little man" problem.

165
00:11:32,775 --> 00:11:34,944
He grew up a little fat kid.

166
00:11:35,027 --> 00:11:37,488
Not a lot of money.
He was always the underdog,

167
00:11:38,447 --> 00:11:42,076
and he just couldn't control
that part of him that needed...

168
00:11:42,827 --> 00:11:43,911
credit.

169
00:11:44,787 --> 00:11:45,787
[man] Michael!

170
00:11:47,498 --> 00:11:49,258
[Smith] All the attention
is going to Michael

171
00:11:49,333 --> 00:11:51,627
and Scottie and Dennis and Phil.

172
00:11:52,545 --> 00:11:54,797
And Krause was growing resentful
about this.

173
00:11:56,215 --> 00:11:58,718
[Vancil] He was good,
but he wasn't good enough

174
00:11:58,801 --> 00:12:00,428
to do it without Michael Jordan.

175
00:12:00,511 --> 00:12:02,847
You could argue that Michael Jordan
was as good at his job

176
00:12:02,930 --> 00:12:05,808
as anyone has ever been at their job,
ever, in anything.

177
00:12:05,891 --> 00:12:08,185
And Krause wants to make the point,

178
00:12:08,269 --> 00:12:11,063
organizations win championships,
not players.

179
00:12:11,147 --> 00:12:16,527
Jerry Krause, Bulls general manager, says,
"Organizations win titles, not players."

180
00:12:16,610 --> 00:12:19,780
Funny thing, I've never seen him post up
and hit a short jump shot.

181
00:12:19,864 --> 00:12:22,491
[reporter] This quote
that was attributed to you...

182
00:12:22,575 --> 00:12:24,660
Well, as you know, David,
it was a misquote.

183
00:12:24,744 --> 00:12:28,914
What I said was that players and coaches
alone don't win championships,

184
00:12:28,998 --> 00:12:30,040
that organizations do.

185
00:12:30,124 --> 00:12:33,169
I do sincerely believe that organizations,
as a whole, win.

186
00:12:33,252 --> 00:12:35,254
One part of it can't win alone.

187
00:12:35,337 --> 00:12:37,465
The guy left the word "alone"
out of there.

188
00:12:38,257 --> 00:12:39,359
- [scoffs]
- [reporter] Right.

189
00:12:39,383 --> 00:12:41,469
He admitted it later on.
"Yeah, I left a word out."

190
00:12:41,552 --> 00:12:44,305
You dumb son of a bitch,
that's what killed the quote.

191
00:12:45,347 --> 00:12:48,768
It sounded like he was making
a very specific point

192
00:12:48,851 --> 00:12:50,519
to a very specific person.

193
00:12:50,603 --> 00:12:54,190
We know that the team is much bigger
than the 15 players.

194
00:12:55,191 --> 00:12:58,486
Those guys who work in the front office,
they were good people,

195
00:12:58,569 --> 00:13:03,949
but the most important part
of the process is the players.

196
00:13:04,033 --> 00:13:09,205
So, for him to say that is offensive
to the way that I approach the game.

197
00:13:10,289 --> 00:13:14,960
[Wilbon] <i>Krause was picked on an awful lot
during this by Michael and Scottie.</i>

198
00:13:15,044 --> 00:13:18,297
I mean, they made fun of him.
They mocked him. They mocked him openly.

199
00:13:19,006 --> 00:13:21,008
So those are the pills you take
to keep you short.

200
00:13:21,926 --> 00:13:23,511
Or are those diet pills?

201
00:13:26,597 --> 00:13:28,599
Was Jerry Krause a bad guy? No.

202
00:13:29,475 --> 00:13:30,976
He was a good guy. He was fun.

203
00:13:31,060 --> 00:13:35,064
If you saw him interact with your kids,
and saw him, you knew he was a good man.

204
00:13:35,147 --> 00:13:40,194
Jerry Krause was one of the nicest,
kindest, sweetest men I've ever known.

205
00:13:40,778 --> 00:13:45,407
But sometimes, he would love people
who really didn't love him back,

206
00:13:45,491 --> 00:13:46,909
and it would disappoint him.

207
00:13:47,368 --> 00:13:48,661
[reporter] Did he love Phil?

208
00:13:49,537 --> 00:13:51,205
Well, he loved Phil in the beginning,

209
00:13:51,288 --> 00:13:55,459
but then, you know, they developed
a tension between the two of 'em.

210
00:13:55,543 --> 00:13:56,543
Phil,

211
00:13:57,294 --> 00:13:59,171
from a contract standpoint,

212
00:13:59,255 --> 00:14:01,048
wanted to be compensated,

213
00:14:01,632 --> 00:14:06,554
like the other coaches that he had beaten,
and Jerry wasn't going to do that.

214
00:14:07,137 --> 00:14:09,431
In Jerry's mind,
you moved pieces in and out.

215
00:14:09,515 --> 00:14:11,141
You didn't move Michael Jordan pieces.

216
00:14:11,725 --> 00:14:15,229
Phil Jackson? You can move him in and out.
And he was wrong about that.

217
00:14:17,731 --> 00:14:19,191
[Jordan] I said from day one,

218
00:14:19,275 --> 00:14:22,361
if Phil's not coaching,
I'm not gonna be a part of rebuilding.

219
00:14:22,444 --> 00:14:26,156
Phil should be the head coach,
and I shouldn't be put in a position

220
00:14:26,240 --> 00:14:30,369
to have to make a choice to play
for another coach other than Phil Jackson.

221
00:14:30,452 --> 00:14:32,705
Sadly as it may be, I have choices.

222
00:14:33,747 --> 00:14:36,625
You know, and I will not choose to play
for another coach.

223
00:14:38,502 --> 00:14:42,256
I think Jerry was looking forward
to having a clean slate

224
00:14:42,339 --> 00:14:44,592
and going out and, you know, rebuilding.

225
00:14:45,509 --> 00:14:49,054
His relationship with me
had become such a circus.

226
00:14:49,722 --> 00:14:52,182
There was no chance for reconciliation.

227
00:14:52,975 --> 00:14:56,437
All of a sudden, there's this guy from
Iowa State, Tim Floyd, the head coach.

228
00:14:57,104 --> 00:14:59,857
He goes fishing with Jerry Krause,
and I'm like, "What?"

229
00:15:00,441 --> 00:15:04,528
So, Krause clearly
is grooming the next guy.

230
00:15:05,154 --> 00:15:08,240
He's gonna be the next Phil Jackson.

231
00:15:08,949 --> 00:15:11,493
Krause's stepdaughter
gets married that summer.

232
00:15:11,577 --> 00:15:16,373
He invites everybody from the team
and Tim Floyd...

233
00:15:17,249 --> 00:15:20,794
and he doesn't invite Phil Jackson,
the head coach.

234
00:15:21,462 --> 00:15:24,590
I recall that, and I think
that was bad form on Jerry's part.

235
00:15:24,673 --> 00:15:26,342
I'm not sure it bothered Phil that much.

236
00:15:26,425 --> 00:15:29,553
If somebody doesn't invite me
to a wedding, I'd like to thank 'em.

237
00:15:29,637 --> 00:15:30,637
[chuckles]

238
00:15:31,430 --> 00:15:33,891
It was sad that there was
such an acrimonious relationship

239
00:15:33,974 --> 00:15:37,353
because Jerry Krause started
Phil Jackson's NBA coaching career.

240
00:15:38,062 --> 00:15:42,024
Jerry Krause brought him to Chicago
as an assistant coach.

241
00:15:42,650 --> 00:15:45,694
If that hadn't happened, you never
would have heard of Phil Jackson.

242
00:15:47,821 --> 00:15:50,157
[Jackson] You know,
things evolve, people evolve.

243
00:15:50,240 --> 00:15:53,035
They don't stay stagnant
and static in any position.

244
00:15:53,118 --> 00:15:56,705
And more than anything else,
coaches' salaries went like this

245
00:15:56,789 --> 00:15:59,500
and general managers' salaries
might have gone like this.

246
00:15:59,583 --> 00:16:01,710
[Vecsey] Do you think
Jerry Krause resents that?

247
00:16:02,628 --> 00:16:04,338
I'm not gonna speculate on that.

248
00:16:05,589 --> 00:16:09,218
I have tremendous regard for Phil,
personally and professionally.

249
00:16:09,301 --> 00:16:11,512
I really like Phil Jackson,

250
00:16:11,595 --> 00:16:14,515
and I wanted Phil Jackson to come back
and coach the team.

251
00:16:15,265 --> 00:16:18,769
And I just thought that the presence
of Jerry was counterproductive.

252
00:16:18,852 --> 00:16:22,147
I just thought if Phil and I
would sit down and talk, we'd work it out.

253
00:16:22,231 --> 00:16:23,524
And I flew out to Montana.

254
00:16:23,607 --> 00:16:25,943
I offered him the opportunity
to come back.

255
00:16:26,026 --> 00:16:27,778
After weeks of public debate,

256
00:16:27,861 --> 00:16:31,782
many would argue that Bulls owner
Jerry Reinsdorf has come to his senses,

257
00:16:31,865 --> 00:16:36,245
signing Phil Jackson to a one-year deal
to return as coach next season.

258
00:16:37,037 --> 00:16:39,999
Phil is the coach, Jerry's the owner.
Those two needed to talk.

259
00:16:40,082 --> 00:16:43,043
And we got it done,
and we're very happy to have it done.

260
00:16:43,127 --> 00:16:45,713
This will be Phil's last year
as the coach of the Bulls.

261
00:16:45,796 --> 00:16:48,590
At the conclusion of the year,
we'll look towards the future.

262
00:16:49,216 --> 00:16:52,761
Jerry called me to his office and said,
"This is going to be your last year.

263
00:16:52,845 --> 00:16:56,223
I don't care if you win 82 games in a row,
this will be your last year here."

264
00:16:56,306 --> 00:16:59,101
So, I said, "Fine,"
and I walked out of the room.

